The wavelength $\blueD\lambda$, frequency $\maroonD f$, and speed $\goldD v$ of a wave are related by this equation:

$\blueD \lambda = \dfrac{\goldD v}{\maroonD f}$

We are given that $\blueD{\lambda = 0.5\,\text m}$ and $\goldD{v=2\,\dfrac{\text m}{\text s} }$. Let's use that to find $\maroonD f$.
$\begin{align}
\blueD \lambda &= \dfrac{\goldD v}{\maroonD f}
\\\\
\maroonD f &= \dfrac{\goldD v}{\blueD \lambda}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{\left(\goldD{2\,\dfrac{\text m}{\text s}}\right)}{\blueD{0.5\,\text m}}
\\\\
&=4\,\text s^{-1}\\\\
&=4\,\text {Hz}
\end{align}$

The correct answer is $4\,\text{Hz}$.

